The losers remain challengers
HARARE: Before the presidential elections this month, I was convinced that irregularities in the elections would have serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and throughout all of southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe have not received them.
Instead, they have received terrorism.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats from the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
ZANU terrorism is attributable to the rogue elements among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
The result of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), failed to reach the electorate in large parts, particularly in the rural areas.
In addition, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, effectively disempowered hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, especially in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion more than 360,000 people stood in line in Harare and Chitungwiza alone, without being able to cast their ballot.
I continue to doubt the legitimacy of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from placing election observers in 52% of the rural polling stations.
Towards the end of the voting, our party was missing observers in 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all the polling stations that were controlled only by ZANU supporters.
Even at this early stage of our previous investigations, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, most of the votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential elections, in which the incumbent president, Robert Mugabe, emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is seen as illegitimate by them.
The people of Zimbabwe were denied their right to freely and democratically elect a president of their choice.
The struggle over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined and deserve to be recognized for this.
Perhaps it is not too late for this yet.
I am writing this text in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still ignores the will of the people.
No matter what happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and walk the path with them to the end.
Perhaps the government wants to arrest me.
I was also already arrested before the elections for high treason.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the will of the people to reclaim its rights and power.
It is in our hands to carry out a democratic change.
In the coming days we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow ourselves to be overcome by despair.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen are afraid of the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger of the news.
Should it come to that, I only ask the people of Zimbabwe to remain strong and to see through to the end what we have begun together.
There are many heroes among the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who could not be sent away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voice must be heard in the world.
We have walked a very difficult path together in order to achieve democratic change in our country.
In the history of mankind, a people rarely had to endure such violence and at the same time manage to preserve kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But in order for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot simply leave these elections as they are, but they must also not fall into Mugabe's provocation and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not standing alone.
We know that throughout Africa, elections are rigged.
Irregularities, fraud, and deception in elections seem to be the norm in most African states.
In Africa, there is always a crisis somewhere due to elections.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to underhanded means when it is time to grant the people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I promise not to abandon them.
